==Old English==
===Etymology===
From the same Germanic root as [[þeod|þēod]].  Cognate with Old Saxon [[thiodan]], Old Norse [[þjóðann]], Gothic [[𐌸𐌹𐌿𐌳𐌰𐌽𐍃]].

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/ˈðe:oden/}}

===Noun===
{{Latinx|'''þēoden'''}} {{m}} (plural '''[[þeodnas|þēodnas]]''')
# ''(poetic)'' [[prince]], [[lord]], [[ruler]], [[chief]]
#:''Mære þeoden æþeling ærgod unbliðe sæt.''  The famous ruler, the ever-good chieftain, sat dismayed.  (''Beowulf'', ll. 129-130)

